article.description:
lISA Leslie had 18 points and 14 rebounds, leading the Sparks to an
84-72 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Friday night.
article.headline: Sparks win 11th straight against Mercury
article.linkText: Double-doubles by Leslie, Milton help Sparks overpower Mercury
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- After the pressure of a championship season, it takes a lot to faze Lisa Leslie and her Los Angeles teammates.

Leslie had 18 points and 14 rebounds, leading the Sparks to an
84-72 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Friday night.

"We knew we had to crash the boards and try and outrebound this
team in order to just stay in the game,'' she said. "I thought we
did a good job on the boards.''

Leslie did all her scoring in the first 28 minutes, helping the defending WNBA champions open a double-digit lead that stood up. Los Angeles (12-1) won its ninth in a row this year and 11th straight against Phoenix, including two playoff wins in 2000.

DeLisha Milton had 13 points and 14 rebounds for the Sparks,
Mwadi Mabika scored 14 points and Nikki Teasley and Latasha Byears
had 12 each.

"Not showing up is not in our vocabulary,'' Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. "We're going to come and play hard, and if we do that we'll be in every game, so there are no excuses. Champions find a way to win.''

Phoenix's Gordana Grubin matched her career high with 23 points, and Jennifer Gillom had 16 for the Mercury (7-5).

Mercury interim coach Linda Sharp was Los Angeles' first coach,
coaching the Sparks to a 4-7 record before she was fired in July
1997.

The Sparks beat the Mercury by 23 points on Tuesday in the last
game for Cynthia Cooper, who resigned as coach the next day. Sharp,
her top assistant, directed the Mercury to a 62-53 win over Seattle
on Wednesday night.

"L.A. has such good shooters,'' Sharp said. "I think the biggest
difference in the game with their team -- other than the fact that
all five of their starters could probably play on our Olympic team
-- is Latasha Byears. She had 12 points and six rebounds and she
went 6-for-6. You have to pay attention to her.''

Leslie had eight points in the first eight minutes of the second
half, shredding Phoenix's defense for a series of layups. The last
opened a 60-47 lead for the Sparks.

Phoenix got within 70-60 on a putback by Kayte Christensen with
7:28 to go, but Byears answered with a layup, and Tamecka Dixon,
who had all 11 of her points in the second half, hit a 3-pointer
and two free throws in the next 1:50.

The Sparks led most of the first half. Grubin started a 13-2 run
with a three-point play with 6:34 left in the half, and added two
more baskets and an assist.

Gillom hit a 3-pointer with 4:26 to go, completing Phoenix's
turnaround from a six-point deficit to a 38-33 lead.

"We were with them most of the time,'' Grubin said. "We played them better tonight.''
